references: As previously described, we evaluate the ability of our proposed FL workflow to predict the risk of ICU mortality at an early stage. We compare it with the CML and LML approaches on two cohorts of patients (
), using two ES metrics (loss and F1-score) and different time windows
, using the minimum loss for ES, are shown in
. Overall, the results show that our model performs well in the task of early ICU mortality prediction. For example, for FL with
, we obtain an average AUROC of
. It’s important to highlight that due to the class imbalance of
towards the positive class, the baseline value for the AUPRC is
In addition, we yield three conclusions from

While an increasing number of clients results in a decrease in predictive performance over all the metrics in LML, the performance of FL remains close to that of CML, regardless of the number of clients.

The relation between precision and recall is very unstable, which is shown in the fluctuation of the averages and the high standard deviations.
While (i) clearly shows that FL has the potential to improve on LML for early ICU mortality prediction, (ii) and (iii) are further explored in the following experiments.
